---

<ArticleLayout
  lang="en"
  altPath="/blog/ky-thuat-tiep-dat-5-4-3-2-1/"
  title="The 5-4-3-2-1 grounding technique: pull your mind back to now | An Nhịp"
  description="A step-by-step guide to the 5-4-3-2-1 grounding technique for anxiety: 5 things you see, 4 you touch, 3 sounds, 2 smells, 1 taste. With variations and practice tips."
  heading="The 5-4-3-2-1 grounding technique: pull your mind back to now"
  datePublished="2026-07-21"
  sources={sources}
>
  <p>
    Anxiety rarely stays in the present. It pulls you back to yesterday's
    conversation, or throws you forward to tomorrow's meeting, and your body
    reacts as if it were happening right now. The grounding technique does the
    opposite: it uses your five senses to anchor your attention to where you
    actually are.
  </p>

  <h2>How to do 5-4-3-2-1</h2>
  <p>
    Look around and name, out loud or in your head, one group at a time:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>5 things you can see.</strong> The more specific, the better: not
      just "the desk" but "the C-shaped scratch on the desk". Detail forces your
      brain to actually look.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>4 things you can touch.</strong> The fabric of your trousers on
      your thigh, the coolness of the desk, the floor under your feet. Really
      touch them, do not just think about them.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>3 sounds you can hear.</strong> A fan, traffic outside, the sound
      of your own breathing.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>2 smells you can notice.</strong> If there is no clear smell around
      you, you can smell your sleeve or a cup of water, or simply note "neutral
      air".
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>1 taste you can notice.</strong> The taste of tea still in your
      mouth, or take a sip of water and pay attention to its taste.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The whole exercise takes about two to three minutes. Take it slowly: the goal
    is not to finish the list, but to truly pause at each sense.
  </p>

  <h2>Why this technique works</h2>
  <p>
    Your attention has limits. When you actively describe what your senses are
    picking up, less attention is left for the anxious train of thought, and its
    intensity usually drops along with it. This is why 5-4-3-2-1 is recommended
    for people dealing with anxiety by many clinical settings such as the
    University of Rochester Medical Center, and why the World Health Organization
    puts grounding first among the skills in its guide for coping with stress.
  </p>
  <p>
    Grounding does not erase what is making you anxious. It creates a pause quiet
    enough for you to choose your next step clearly, instead of being swept along
    by your thoughts.
  </p>

  <h2>Variations for when the situation is not ideal</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>In a crowded place:</strong> do it entirely in your head, silently,
      with no need to speak. You can shorten it to 3-2-1 (3 things you see, 2 you
      touch, 1 sound).
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>At night, in a dark room:</strong> shift your focus to touch and
      hearing: the blanket on your skin, the temperature of the air, sounds near
      and far.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>When it is hard to focus:</strong> combine it with an object in
      your hand (keys, a small stone) and describe it in detail: heavy or light,
      smooth or rough, warm or cold.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Tips to make the technique actually useful</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Practice before you need it.</strong> Like any skill, grounding
      works best once it feels familiar. Try it once a day at an ordinary moment.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Do not grade yourself.</strong> If an anxious thought comes back
      partway through, that is not a failure. Notice it, then return to the sense
      you were on.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Pair it with slow breathing.</strong> One round of
      <a href={withBase('/en/blog/breathing-exercises-for-anxiety/')}>belly breathing</a>
      before you start helps your body settle enough to observe.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>When to get more support</h2>
  <p>
    If anxiety or a feeling of "being disconnected from reality" happens often,
    lasts a long time, or makes you avoid more and more activities, talk to a
    doctor or a mental health professional. Self-help techniques are a first line
    of support, not a replacement for a professional assessment.
  </p>

  <h2>Guided practice in An Nhịp</h2>
  <p>
    The <a href={withBase('/en/')}>An Nhịp</a> app walks you through each sense of
    the 5-4-3-2-1 exercise at a slow pace, alongside breathing exercises and a
    CBT thought record. Free, no account, and your data stays on your device. The
    app interface is currently in Vietnamese.
    <a href={withBase('/en/download/')}>Get the Android version here</a>.
  </p>
</ArticleLayout>
